</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wezloc@themagicianstower>WEZLOC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1286<br> <font color=#333333>(11/21/02 8:09:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7926.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: debuffs vs lures</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Its not. The spell line really is a Shaman line that we were given because they couldn't work out who else should have it as far as I can tell, or they just eneded something else to round off the mage class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nah I disagree with this. I think the reason mages have the Malosini line of spells is because we needed them. We don't have the options that wizards so they gave us this debuff instead of making two seperate spell lines. Kinda like just because shamans get slow first doesn't mean that it is a shaman spell line that was handed down to others. <br>
<br>
Malosini type spells were given to mages I feel mostly because of our pets. All pets have a damage spell, and because they were lower in level then most things the mage would be fighting the debuff helps pets to land spells better i.e. earth pet root. I think as time has moved forward this line of spells has become a main stay spell line for mages and I have Malosini up at all times. I almost never get resisted if I debuff a mob first, and it is a key feature that a mage brings to a group that is often over looked. I debuff out of habit now so normally even if we have a shaman he will slow after my debuff call.  Mages are not totally limited in there ability to do cold based damage. The epic pet has a cold based proc, that procs often. I think that is a key feature, and is a clear statement that they wish for mages to have cold based ability just differently then druids/wizards. I would not trade Malosini or my water pet for a cold based nuke.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Have a look at the PoP spells. They are almost (totally?) all extensions to existing spell series'. Shifting and adding spell lines is something they said they were avoiding in the last FF developer's meeting:<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well I think they realized instead of expanding on abilities it is best to make other current abilities stronger. I think they have seen the error of their ways in terms of bad spell lines. That is why no upgrades to useless spell lines like Monster Summoning, and the magic based dots. Also consider our new direct damage ability, and I believe that is why we were not given a new highend unresistable mala type spell. Also so far they seemed to have hit the spot on mob resist. I have had zero problems nuking experience mobs or boss mobs once debuffed.<br>
<br>
Another thing we should consider as well is unlike wizards mages have fire/magic, then <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>cold based pets</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. The thing we always leave out is that we have the best melee damage like no other casting class. Our ability to attack a mob via melee is approaching the highend PC level. Wizards do not have that ability, and that is just another reason why mages should not have cold based nukes. I would not turn one down but I no longer see the need for a cold based dd spell line.<br>
<br>
Wezloc<br>
<br>
